tldr: The user requested to add Cursor rules to their project. The assistant
  analyzed the Next.js SaaS starter project and created a detailed set of
  contextual Cursor rules, organized into specific files for different aspects
  like project conventions, database, authentication, payments, components, and
  API routes.
overview: The user wanted to integrate Cursor rules into their Next.js SaaS
  starter project. The assistant began by inspecting the project for existing
  Cursor configurations and then performed a deep dive into key files like
  , database schema, middleware, and queries to understand the
  project's unique tech stack and coding patterns. Based on this analysis, the
  assistant generated a comprehensive set of six Markdown Cursor (MDC) rule
  files. These rules cover general project conventions, Drizzle ORM database
  patterns, JWT-based authentication, Stripe payment integration, UI component
  best practices (including Server vs. Client Components), and API route handler
  guidelines. Each rule file is configured with specific  to ensure
  contextual application, providing relevant guidance without overwhelming the
  user.
